{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1012"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1012"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.31,0.58,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53489"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44489"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents with a one day history of increasing abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and widespread over all the abdomen. His medical history includes a colectomy for carcinoma six years earlier, type II diabetes and hypertension. He takes metformin and irbesartan. On examination he looks ill, with a blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg, irregular pulse of 90/min and temperature, 37.4C. He is obese and the abdominal findings are difficult to interpret, but there does appear to be widespread tenderness. A plain film is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gallstone ileus","Sigmoid volvulus","Mesenteric ischaemia","Necrotising pancreatitis","Acute acalculous cholecystitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key finding on the X-ray is an abnormal gas pattern in the region of the liver. The distribution of the gas suggests that it is in the portal venous system. The gas pattern in the large bowel is normal. \u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for the gas in the portal venous system. The clinical picture is consistent with such a diagnosis. The patient\u0027s age, history of cardiovascular risk factors (diabetes, hypertension), and the sudden onset of severe, widespread abdominal pain are all typical features of mesenteric ischaemia. The presence of portal venous gas in this context is highly suggestive of intestinal necrosis, which is a late and ominous sign in mesenteric ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with gas in the biliary tree (pneumobilia) but not the portal vein. While pneumobilia can sometimes be difficult to differentiate from portal venous gas, the absence of any dilated loops of small bowel on the X-ray would exclude gallstone ileus. Additionally, the clinical presentation of gallstone ileus typically includes intermittent abdominal pain and vomiting, which are not prominent features in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with abdominal distension, constipation, and a characteristic \u0027coffee bean\u0027 appearance on abdominal X-ray. None of these features are present in this case. Furthermore, sigmoid volvulus would not explain the presence of portal venous gas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause severe abdominal pain and systemic illness, but it is not typically associated with hepatic portal venous gas. The X-ray findings in necrotising pancreatitis may include a sentinel loop (a dilated loop of small bowel adjacent to the pancreas) or the colon cut-off sign, neither of which are seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute acalculous cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with portal venous gas. While it can occur in critically ill patients and cause right upper quadrant pain, the widespread nature of the pain and the X-ray findings in this case are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe usual predisposing factors for gas entering the portal venous system in intestinal ischaemia are mucosal damage and necrosis, bowel distension, and proliferation of gas-forming bacteria. To be visible on a plain abdominal radiograph implies a large volume of gas and an aggressive underlying pathology. When seen in conjunction with mesenteric ischaemia, the presence of portal venous gas often indicates a poor prognosis with high mortality rates. Urgent surgical consultation and further imaging (such as CT angiography) are typically required to confirm the diagnosis and guide management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gas in the portal venous system is frequently a sign of an intra-abdominal ischaemic process.","Mesenteric ischaemia is a surgical emergency with high mortality rates, especially in elderly patients with comorbidities.","The clinical presentation of mesenteric ischaemia often includes severe abdominal pain disproportionate to physical examination findings."],"references":["Abboud B, El Hachem J, Yazbeck T, et al. Hepatic portal venous gas: Physiopathology, etiology, prognosis and treatment. World J Gastroenterol 2009; 15:3585-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19653334/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53489"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1012"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15325"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15325"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/70026636-16fb-475d-a890-527750aa4721.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/70026636-16fb-475d-a890-527750aa4721.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":338,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53489"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T14:58:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T08:37:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1012"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"sel